<H3> <TI>   Preparation for Renewed Framework Talks Mentioned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Preparation for Renewed Framework Talks Mentioned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604061794 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 6 Apr 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0604061794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 6 April Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] On 5 April, a government source commented on the 
resumption of the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks, stating: 
"We have nothing to do. As far as Japan is concerned, it is 
important that the United States see Japan's position in an 
economic package to be compiled in June." The source indicated 
that the framework talks will not be resumed earlier than June, 
at which time Japan is scheduled to compile a final package of 
measures to reduce its current account surplus, including 
market-opening measures through deregulation. 
  In response, Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime minister and 
concurrently foreign minister, said at a news conference 
following a cabinet meeting on the same day: "It is 
inappropriate to say we have nothing to do. Each ministry and 
agency is trying to come up with such measures as deregulation. 
We have a chance to discuss the issue on various occasions. It 
is important for us to discuss what efforts are now being made." 
He thus criticized the remarks by the government source. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

