<H3> <TI>   SDPJ Leader Wary of Sending Group to DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ Leader Wary of Sending Group to DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604060594 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 6 Apr 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0604060594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 6 April Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] In connection with the issue of North Korea's 
suspected nuclear development, some legislators affiliated with 
the ruling Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] have 
discussed the possibility of sending a delegation to North 
Korea; but on 5 April, one ruling party after another argued 
that sending such a delegation to North Korea should be handled 
cautiously. Commenting on the intraparty discussion at an 5 
April news conference, Tomiichi Murayama, chairman of the SDPJ, 
stressed: "We intend to cautiously study what our party can do 
after grasping the situation a little more clearly." SDPJ Vice 
Chairman Inoue recently met with a high-ranking North Korean 
official in Beijing. It is said that during the meeting, Inoue 
got the impression the North Korean official showed a 
forward-looking attitude toward a visit by the delegation. 
However, the remark made by Chairman Murayama at the news 
conference indicated his cautious attitude toward sending the 
delegation to North Korea. During the news conference, Chairman 
Murayama also stated: "If there is a role to be played by the 
SDPJ in easing tensions in Asia, the SDPJ is willing to play 
that role aggressively." 

</TEXT>

