Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 April 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction Continues to F-15 Crash in Okinawa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction Continues to F-15 Crash in Okinawa </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Protests Spreading </H4>

<F P=102> OW0604010694 Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO in Japanese 5 Apr Evening 
Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0604010694 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] It has been learned that the F-15 fighter which 
crashed after taking off from Kadena Air Base had been flying 
eastward shortly before the crash. With Okinawa Highway and 
Okinawa City located near the crash site, the crash could have 
caused a terrible disaster. A resident who witnessed the crash 
has indicated the flight route of the aircraft on a map. As 
regards the accident, the Kadena Air Base Public Affairs Office 
stated: "An investigation into the cause of the crash is under 
way, and there is nothing to comment on at this moment." 
  Since the military aircraft crashed near residential areas, 
Okinawans continued to take angry action on 5 April. 
  The Okinawa prefectural government takes the crash seriously 
and sent Tatsuo Matayoshi, chief of the Public Affairs Office, 
to Kadena Air Base on the morning of 5 April to express regret 
to Jeffrey Cliver, commander of the 18th Wing, and to ask the 
commander to conduct a through investigation into the crash. 
  On 4 April, the Okinawa City Assembly held an extraordinary 
session; on the morning of 5 April, the Kadena Town Assembly and 
the Chatan Town Assembly held extraordinary sessions to 
unanimously adopt resolutions. In this manner, protests against 
the crash are now spreading to cities and towns located near 
Kadena Air Base. 
  On the morning of 5 April, labor and peace organizations 
staged emergency rallies to protest the crash on the so-called 
"hill where the Japan-U.S. Security Treaty is seen" along the 
runway of the air base. 
  Officials from the Okinawa Federation of the opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party, the Okinawa Federation of the ruling 
Social Democratic Party of Japan, and the Okinawa Federation of 
the ruling Komeito have visited the Naha Defense Facilities 
Administration Bureau to demand the removal of F-15 fighters, an 
investigation into cause of the crash, and the prevention of a 
recurrence of the crash. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

