<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Rebut USTR Trade Barrier Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo To Rebut USTR Trade Barrier Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0504102694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 5 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0504102694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government has started preparing a written 
refutation of the U.S. Trade Representative [USTR] Office's 
"National Trade Estimate Report on Foreign Trade Barriers," 
which was released late last month. The Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry [MITI] thinks that "the 
unilateral report has been compiled based on false premises." 
The refutation will be formulated as a report and will be sent 
to the U.S. Government as early as mid-April. It will convey 
Tokyo's position at every level of upcoming bilateral 
negotiations. 
  In the report on trade barriers, the USTR listed 43 items 
deemed to be Japan's "trade barriers," and, in a follow-up news 
conference, USTR Counsel General Ira Shapiro stressed that 
"Japan's trade barriers are extremely numerous compared to those 
of the seven advanced nations." 
  In reaction, the government criticized the U.S. report, 
noting that "the definition of `trade barriers' is unclear and 
the report has been written based on the wishes of U.S. 
industrial circles" (as stated by MITI). Moreover, the 
government said that individual trade barriers are "based on 
false premises." As for government procurement of medical and 
telecommunications equipment, which has been newly added to the 
trade barriers list, the government noted that the "U.S. request 
concerning this sector has already been incorporated into our 
economic reform guidelines." The government intends to convey 
the aforementioned points to the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

