<H3> <TI>   Military Support Talks With Perry `Expected' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Military Support Talks With Perry `Expected' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704102394 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 6 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0704102394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A senior Foreign Ministry official said on 5 April 
that in connection with the DPRK's suspected nuclear weapons 
development, Japan and the United States might discuss the issue 
of concluding an "acquisition and cross-servicing agreement 
(ACSA)" during U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry's stay in 
Japan, which is scheduled to begin from 19 April. If the ACSA 
is signed, Japan can provide fuel and services to the U.S. 
forces. 
  It is expected that if economic sanctions are imposed 
against 
North Korea, Japan will be asked to supply fuel to the U.S. 
warships participating in naval blockade. The United States has 
long been asking Japan to sign the ACSA. Meanwhile, as tension 
has mounted on the Korean peninsula, opinion has prevailed 
within government offices, such as the Foreign Ministry, that a 
rear-echelon support system should be established immediately. 
  The government will seriously consider the conclusion of the 
ACSA if the United States renews its request. However, the same 
Foreign Ministry official said: "Discussions within the 
government will not be smooth." 

</TEXT>

