<H3> <TI>   Protests of F-15 Crash in Okinawa Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Protests of F-15 Crash in Okinawa Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Urasoe City Adopts Resolution </H4>

<F P=102> OW0604145194 Naha OKINAWA TIMES in Japanese 6 Apr 94 Evening 
Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0604145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha OKINAWA TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Urasoe -- The Urasoe City Assembly (with Ichiro 
Akamine as chairman) held an emergency meeting on the morning of 
6 April and unanimously adopted a statement and a resolution of 
protest against the incident in which an F-15 jet fighter 
crashed the previous day. 
  In the statement and resolution, the city assembly demanded 
that "a thorough investigation be made to determine the cause of 
the accident, clarification be made to the people of Okinawa 
Prefecture, and flights and exercises by F-15's be completely 
suspended until the cause is determined." It also demanded that 
"the unit to which the crashed F-15 belongs be withdrawn from 
Okinawa." 
  Copies of the statement are to be sent to the prime minister 
and the governor of Okinawa, while copies of the resolution are 
to be sent to the U.S. ambassador to Japan, the Kadena Air Base 
commander, and other officials. 

</TEXT>

