<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   INTEC Expands Service Area With U.S. Tie-Up </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    INTEC Expands Service Area With U.S. Tie-Up </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0092A Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 Mar 94 p 
8--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0092A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] INTEC will be mutually linked through packet 
switching networks operated by Sprint International, the 
international division of Sprint, a U.S. long-distance telephone 
company. Linkage of networks of the two companies will provide 
for an integrated system offering international data 
communications services. They will offer improved services 
encompassing an expansion of service areas and increased 
sophistication in services offered. 
  INTEC and Sprint signed an "International Communications 
Mutual Linkage Contract." Based on this contract, INTEC's packet 
switching net known as "Ace Telenet" will link up with and use 
the "Sprint Net Service"--operated by Japan Sprint, Sprint 
International's Japanese subsidiary--as a gateway. This 
arrangement will enable INTEC to provide services without 
changing its status as a domestic special class II operator. 
  INTEC's service area will expand to over 40 countries. 
Currently, it services 10 countries, including the United 
States, Great Britain and Southeast Asia, but the service areas 
will be expanded geographically to include Australia, South 
America, the European continent and the former Soviet republics. 
  Services offered will be expanded from the current rate 
system based on volume of usage to fixed rate systems and rates 
for circuit use which bypasses Japan. Companies with branches in 
multiple overseas locations can utilize a variety of services 
with options covering such aspects as purpose, data volume, 
optimum linkage times as well as arrange direct communication 
links between their overseas branches and billing and settlement 
of service fees on a consolidated basis via their Japan 
headquarters. 
  INTEC is scheduled to initiate the new services effective 
the 
first part of April. It claims that its fees will be 10 to 30 
percent lower than those of other long-distance service 
companies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

