<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   BOJ Governor Mieno's Speech Criticizes Banks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    BOJ Governor Mieno's Speech Criticizes Banks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Banks Counter Criticism </H4>

<F P=102> 942B0090B Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 Mar 94 p 
7--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942B0090B </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Excerpt] Federation of Bankers' Association of Japan 
President Okuda Responds to BOJ Governor's Criticism About 
"Imitating"--"Innovative Services Could Be Established If 
Controls Did Not Exist" 
  In response to BOJ Governor Mieno's criticism of financial 
institutions' tendencies to imitate each other, Federation of 
Bankers' Association of Japan President and Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank 
President Masashi Okuda in a press conference on the 29th [of 
March] said, "Banks have exercised commensurate creativity 
amidst limited freedom under a variety of controls." President 
Okuda also pointed out that "If management's options are 
expanded by the decontrol of financial systems, competition 
should increase above previous levels and we should witness the 
creation of innovative services which are peculiar to Japan." 
  In his speech on the 24th [of March], Governor Mieno stated, 
"The reason why it is difficult for Japanese financial 
institutions to create financial innovations is that there is a 
relative lack of a tendency to utilize competitive market 
principles." When asked for his thoughts on this statement, 
President Okuda said, "Banks have been restricted by a variety 
of controls such as licensing systems from the standpoint of 
protection for depositors and maintenance of confidence and 
order," in pointing out that regulation by banking authorities 
prevented the creation of innovative services. Finally, he 
stated that the "industry would like to enhance the quality of 
financial services by challenging themselves to offer new 
services" through such actions as review of bank operations and 
decontrol of interest rates. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

