Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canada's Minister MacLaren Comments on Trade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canada's Minister MacLaren Comments on Trade </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Says U.S. Wrong To Seek Targets </H4>

<F P=102> OW0704064994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0638 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704064994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 7 KYODO -- The United States is wrong 
in seeking bilateral trade targets with Japan, but that does not 
mean Japan can keep its markets to itself, Canada's trade 
minister said Thursday [7 April]. 
  Roy MacLaren, Canadian minister for international trade, 
said 
in Tokyo that Canada "regrets" the revival of "Super 301" trade 
legislation by U.S. President Bill Clinton as well as the U.S. 
insistence on setting numerical trade targets in bilateral trade 
with Japan. But he quickly added, "there is broad recognition, 
including by the Japanese Government, that meaningful action to 
address Japan's chronic current account surpluses is essential." 
  Canada, MacLaren said, favors a more open, international 
Japan and suggested that the country must bring forth 
"meaningful regulatory and administrative reform," particularly 
in distribution, transportation, communications and financial 
services. 
  Speaking to Japanese and Canadian executives, MacLaren 
emphasized that while he does not support the U.S. approach to 
negotiations with Japan, "Japan remains limited by regulations, 
many of which appear to us as quite unnecessary." 
  Meeting reporters after his address, MacLaren said both 
Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata 
outlined Japan's commitment to deregulation in meetings with 
him. Detailed plans were not presented, but an outline for 
changes over the next five years were shown him, he said. 
  At later meetings with International Trade and Industry 
Minister Hiroshi Kumagai and Construction Minister Kozo 
Igarashi, MacLaren said he would press for significant action in 
reducing regulatory barriers to the expansion of Canadian 
exports of building products, other materials, and value-added 
goods to Japan. 
  Touching on the market access measures Japan released last 
week, the minister said Canada "welcomes them." But, he added, 
"they hardly meet what we regard as a desirable goal -- they 
don't go very far -- but are a step." 
  He also stressed that Canada supports decentralization in 
Japan and pointed to his visit to the southernmost main island 
of Kyushu earlier this week as underlining the benefits small 
and medium Canadian companies can obtain if they don't have to 
do business "through Tokyo's great trading companies." At the 
regional level, he suggested, business-to-business ventures and 
agreements "come quickly." 
  MacLaren will host a roundtable on Japan-Canada business and 
economic relations Friday and meet with several business leaders 
before departing Saturday for Morocco where he will represent 
Canada at the signing of the Uruguay Round multilateral trade 
agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5042 </DOCNO>
