<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canada's Minister MacLaren Comments on Trade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canada's Minister MacLaren Comments on Trade </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Urges Trade Multilateral Rules </H4>

<F P=102> OW0704054194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0531 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704054194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 7 KYODO -- Canada's Trade Minister 
Thursday [7 April] criticized U.S. calls to introduce "numerical 
targets" to measure foreign access to Japanese markets, Foreign 
Ministry officials said Thursday. Canadian Minister for 
International Trade Roy MacLaren voiced the concern in separate 
meetings with Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata, the officials said. 
  MacLaren told Hosokawa and Hata that Canada considers it 
important to promote trade under multilateral rules, they said. 
  He expressed appreciation for Hata's remarks that Japan 
intends to report the results of bilateral discussions to other 
nations, and added that Canada opposes U.S. calls on Japan for 
numerical targets or to introduce managed trade because such 
moves affect third parties, they said. Canada has repeatedly 
told Washington of its opposition, MacLaren was quoted as saying. 
  Hata, during an hour-long meeting with MacLaren, said he has 
told U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor that agreements 
between the United States and Japan should not affect other 
nations, so Japan disagrees with numerical targets, the 
officials said. 
  He also referred to the successful Uruguay Round of 
multilateral trade talks and said managed trade should be 
avoided. 
  MacLaren voiced expectations that Japan continue to promote 
deregulation, they said, and Hosokawa and Hata told MacLaren 
that Japan is trying to do so. 
  The trade minister, who arrived in Tokyo on Wednesday after 
visiting Fukuoka in western Japan, told the Japanese leaders 
that Canada wants to strengthen ties not only with the Tokyo 
area but also with local economies, they said. 
  MacLaren invited Hosokawa and Hata to visit Canada, they 
said. 
  MacLaren has been in Japan since Tuesday on the last leg of 
a 
three-nation Asian tour that also took him to China and South 
Korea. He is scheduled to leave Japan on Saturday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

