<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Kazakh President's Visit Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Kazakh President's Visit Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hosokawa Meets With President </H4>

<F P=102> OW0704130594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1008 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 7 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa pledged on Thursday [7 April] to lend Kazakhstan up to 
12.98 billion yen to help it improve railroad transportation and 
tackle pollution from thermal power stations, Foreign Ministry 
officials said. Hosokawa made the pledge in a meeting with 
Kazakhstan President Nursultan Nazarbayev, the officials said. 
  Japan will extend the loan to support the central Asian 
nation's economic reform efforts and to help its environmental 
preservation measures, they said. 
  Of the total, 7.23 billion yen will be set aside for a 
project to improve railroad transportation. The project aims at 
supplying equipment necessary to expand Druzhba station at the 
border with China which serves as the base for material 
transportation, and to repair and improve the track. 
  Another 5.74 billion yen will be for a project to tackle air 
pollution from the Ekibastuz thermal power station in northern 
Kazakhstan, the officials said. 
  The project aims at installing electric dust collectors and 
denitrification and desulfurization equipment at the power 
station. Despite the use of coal for thermal power generation, 
sufficient environmental preservation measures have not been 
taken in Kazakhstan since it became independent with the breakup 
of the Soviet Union, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5045 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas067_a_94008" </HT>


