<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Kazakh President's Visit Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Kazakh President's Visit Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Bank Agrees To Extend Loans </H4>

<F P=102> OW0704095094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0809 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 7 KYODO -- The Export-Import Bank of 
Japan signed Thursday [6 April] to extend two untied loans worth 
28.5 billion yen to Kazakhstan, bank officials said Thursday [7 
April]. 
  Of the total, a 18.8 billion yen loan will be made with an 
arrangement of the International Monetary Fund. The remaining 
9.7 billion yen loan will be cofinanced with the International 
Bank for Reconstruction and Development in its rehabilitation 
loan program. 
  These loans are the bank's first financial assistance to 
central Asian countries. The loans are also under the "Funds 
for Development Initiative" launched by the Japanese Government 
in June, 1993. 

</TEXT>

