<H3> <TI>   Silk Trade Talks With PRC End With Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Silk Trade Talks With PRC End With Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704131594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1240 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 7 KYODO -- Japan agreed Thursday [7 
April] to import 7.15 million square meters of silk goods from 
China in fiscal 1994, the Trade Ministry said. The sum compares 
with 7.2 million square meters in the previous year, the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI) said, 
summing up two days of silk trade talks in Tokyo between Japan 
and China. 
  The accord also calls for Japan to import 10,500 bales of 
Chinese-made silk thread for the year which started April 1, 
down from 11,500 bales in fiscal 1993. 
  Raw silk shipments to Japan in the current year will total 
19,000 bales, up from 13,500 bales, MITI said. One bale weighs 
60 kilograms. 

</TEXT>

