<H3> <TI>   Farm Cooperatives Oppose Uruguay Round Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Farm Cooperatives Oppose Uruguay Round Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604122294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1148 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0604122294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 6 KYODO -- The Central Union of 
Agricultural Cooperatives registered its opposition Wednesday [6 
April] to an accord to be signed by Japan that will bring the 
seven-year-long Uruguay Round of world trade talks to a 
conclusion, officials of the union said. They said Hakaru 
Toyoda, president of the union, met with Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi Takemura and Eijiro Hata, minister of the agriculture, 
forestry and fisheries. 
  The union said it opposes the accord because it will lead to 
liberalization of Japan's markets for farm produce, the 
officials said. Toyoda urged the government to, instead, 
implement policies that will create a stable working environment 
for farmers and adopt farm trade laws that secure the survival 
of Japan's agricultural industry. 
  The Uruguay Round accord, which comprises a broad range of 
trading rules agreed on at talks sponsored by the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, will be signed in Marrakech, 
Morocco at a ministerial meeting to be held April 12-15. 

</TEXT>

