<H3> <TI>   Minister Fujii Receives OECD Secretary General </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Fujii Receives OECD Secretary General </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0504124794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1232 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0504124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 5 KYODO -- Finance Minister Hirohisa 
Fujii told OECD leader Jean-Claude Paye Tuesday [5 April] the 
Japanese Government is considering full-scale tax cuts in years 
beyond fiscal 1995, officials said. The officials said Fujii 
and Paye, secretary general of the Paris-based Organization for 
Economic Cooperation and Development, exchanged views on the 
economic situation. 
  The government of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa has been 
under pressure to implement tax cuts on a continuing basis to 
stimulate domestic demand, thereby increasing market potential 
for imports. 
  Fujii told Paye the government is considering full-scale tax 
cuts in fiscal 1995 and onward, the officials said. Legislation 
for a 20 percent reduction in income and residential taxes for 
this year has already cleared the Diet. 
  Fujii was quoted as telling Paye the government considers it 
necessary to raise the 3.0 percent consumption tax rate to help 
ease the tax burden on middle-class wage earners, the officials 
said. Paye, on a regular visit to Japan for consultations with 
Japanese leaders, expressed hope that tax cuts will help 
stimulate consumer spending in Japan and expand domestic demand, 
they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

