<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Business Leader Cites Mieno on Economy Prospects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Business Leader Cites Mieno on Economy Prospects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604101294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0936 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0604101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 6 KYODO -- Bank of Japan Governor 
Yasushi Mieno told business leaders Wednesday [6 April] he sees 
bright signs in corporate sentiment and such is reflected in the 
real economy, a business leader said. 
  Mieno pointed to a slight increase in exports against the 
backdrop of a strong U.S. economy and progress in reducing 
corporate inventories and corporate restructuring, according to 
Kenji Kawakatsu, vice chairman of the Federation of Economic 
Organizations (Keidanren). Kawakatsu cited Mieno as saying that 
was clearly not the picture a year ago. 
  But Mieno reportedly added he will continue to watch those 
bright signs to determine whether they will lead to a 
full-fledged economic recovery. 
  Mieno also said the strength of the yen in currency markets 
continues to put pressure on the economy and stressed the 
importance of private business vigor to ensure economic 
recovery, according to Kawakatsu. 

</TEXT>

