<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official: Economy `Not Yet Set To Recover' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official: Economy `Not Yet Set To Recover' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704094894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0922 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704094894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 7 KYODO -- Japan's economy is not yet 
set to recover but a further fall is unlikely, Vice Finance 
Minister Jiro Saito said Thursday [7 April]. "As we have been 
saying, the economy is unlikely to deteriorate further," Saito 
told a scheduled news conference, referring to remarks Wednesday 
by Bank of Japan Governor Yasushi Mieno. 
  The BOJ chief virtually declared an end to the three-year 
recession by saying the economy is showing signs of hitting 
bottom. 
  But Saito remained cautious about projecting recovery as did 
Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii when he met reporters after 
Mieno. "There may be some differences in nuances, but they 
(Mieno's comments) are basically the same as the latest 
(monthly) economic report by the Economic Planning Agency," 
Saito said. 
  "Mieno also did not completely mention a recovery," Saito 
said. Under these circumstances, Saito stressed the government 
must steadily implement the record 15.25 trillion yen stimulus 
package and enact the fiscal 1994 budget as early as possible to 
put the economy on a "full-fledged recovery track." 
  Considering the tax issue, Saito welcomed the recent 
direction indicated by the Social Democratic Party (SDP) to 
accepting a consumption tax hike. But he declined to comment 
further on ongoing discussions among the ruling coalition 
parties which are to decide on a full-scale tax reform by the 
end of the year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

