<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Denounces U.S. Press Reporting on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Denounces U.S. Press Reporting on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0704035794 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2200 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0704035794 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2200 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to reports, U.S. papers have recently came 
out publicly with bellicose assertions opposing our country. 
  According to reports by the Voice of America on 4 April, THE 
NEW YORK TIMES ran amok in an editorial that the United States 
should at once bomb North Korea's nuclear facilities. U.S. 
TODAY has said this and that on the inevitability of unleashing 
a war on the Korean peninsula. 
  A U.S. defense magazine, AVIATION WEEK AND SPACE TECHNOLOGY, 
on 5 April reported that the United States has worked out a plan 
to deploy ultramodern ground equipment to South Korea so as to 
directly analyze information sent by a spy satellite. 
  In an interview with National Broadcasting Company [NBC] 
Television Network on 3 April, U.S. Defense Secretary Perry, who 
has carelessly set out war outbursts [pokon] and disguisedly 
revealed a warmonger's true color, again brought up North 
Korea's fictitious nuclear development. He said that even at 
the cost of triggering a war on the Korean peninsula, the United 
States will suspend the development of nuclear arms. Raving 
that the United States will not rely on diplomatic means but 
take the road of pressuring North Korea, including imposing 
sanctions, he let loose outbursts that the United States will 
not exclude the possibility of a preemptive military strike on 
North Korea. 
  Timed to coincide with the U.S. military heads' war 
outbursts, the U.S. papers' bellicose assertions opposing us, 
which are being revealed more nakedly, provoke just vigilance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5072 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas067_c_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Press, Secretary Perry's Remarks Condemned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Press, Secretary Perry's Remarks Condemned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0704051294 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0454 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0704051294 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Paid Trumpeters Dancing to the Tune of Warmaniacs" -- KCNA </F>
headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, April 7 (KCNA) -- THE NEW YORK TIMES in 
an editorial kicked up a war hysteria, crying for a prompt 
bombing raid on the nuclear sites of North Korea by the United 
States, according to Voice of America April 4. 
  USA TODAY also clamoured about "the inevitability of a war 
on 
the Korean peninsula." 
  The U.S. Defence Secretary William Perry has let loose a 
string of bellicose outbursts, fully revealing his true color as 
a warmaniac. In an interview with the U.S. NBC Television on 
April 3, he again brought forward the fiction of "nuclear arms 
development by North Korea" and declared that the United States 
was ready for a war adventure to check it. 
  Responding to the bellicose utterances of a U.S. brasshat, 
paid trumpeters of the United States are coming out with 
nonsensical arguments against the DPRK. 
  The very one bringing the dark clouds of a nuclear war over 
the Korean peninsula is the United States which is threatening 
the DPRK with nuclear weapons. 
  In vociferating about the fictitious "nuclear weapons 
development" by North Korea, the U.S. warlikers seek to find a 
pretext to stifle the socialist system of the DPRK. 
  Ignoring this stark fact, paid trumpeters of the U.S. are 
dancing to the drum-beating of the warmaniacs. This shows that 
they are despicable hackwriters who have thrown away justice and 
conscience, impartiality and truth of the press like a pair of 
wornout shoes for a few dollars. 
  The trumpeters bribed by the U.S. bellicose elements would 
be 
well advised to act with discretion, drawing a proper lesson 
from the doom of such warmaniacs as Hitler and Tojo who perished 
in the flame of the war of aggression kindled by them to 
subjugate other countries and nations and from the doom of the 
hackwriters who played into their hands. 

</TEXT>

