<H3> <TI>   Analyst on Japan's `Desire' for Military Power </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Analyst on Japan's `Desire' for Military Power </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0604103094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1021 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0604103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Japan's Desire To Become Military Power Unchanged"--KCNA </F>
headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, April 6 (KCNA) -- Japanese Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa never let a chance pass by without claiming 
that "Japan would never be a military power" and "Japan should 
set the pace in worldwide arms cut." He is straining every nerve 
to convince the Asian nations in particular that Japan will not 
choose to be a military power. Commenting on this, a NODONG 
SINMUN analyst today says: But what Japan is doing totally 
gainsays this. In fact, its armed forces are being beefed up 
and its conversion into a military power is being hastened. 
  The analyst points out: 
  The Japanese Government decided to allocate 45,000 million 
dollars to military expenditure this year. 
  It must not be overlooked that Japan is arming the 
"self-defence forces" with long-range attack weapons. 
  Nuclear armament is an immediate main goal in converting 
Japan into a military power. Having completed material and 
technical preparations for the manufacture of nuclear weapons, 
Japan developed and launched even a nuclear-capable space rocket. 
  After paving the way for the dispatch of troops overseas, 
Japan has taken a mobilisation posture so that it may send 
large combat units anywhere and any time. 
  In categorically denying Japan's scheme to convert itself 
into a military power, the Japanese authorities seek to lull the 
concern of the Asian peoples over the danger of its aggression 
and dull their caution. 
  It is the ulterior intention of the Japanese ruling quarters 
to become a military power and realise their old dream of "the 
greater east Asia coprosperity sphere" with strength. 
  The Asian people are watching the movement of Japan with 
heightened vigilance. 
  The conversion of Japan into a military power and its 
overseas aggression will lead it to self-destruction. 
  Japan must act with discretion, not forgetting the lesson of 
history. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

