<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Technical Advances in Spring Plowing Praised </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Technical Advances in Spring Plowing Praised </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0704001394 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1524 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0704001394 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 6 (KCNA) -- Spring ploughing is in 
full swing in the Yonbaek plain. 
  The cooperative farms in the plain have tilled vast tracts 
of 
paddy and non-paddy fields in a few days by raising the 
operation rate of the tractors. 
  The plain, known as a granary on the West Coast, covers 
broad 
areas of Chongdan, Yonan and Paechon counties, South Hwanghae 
Province, the central western part of Korea. 
  In the preliberation days the peasants there toiled with 
dull 
hoes and wooden ploughs. 
  The comprehensive mechanization of agriculture, which began 
making a rapid development after the publication of the 
socialist rural theses in February 1964, has now reached the 
stage of completion. In Paechon County the number of the 
tractors increased 3.1 times, lorries 7.4 times, rice harvestors 
10 times and weeding machines 15 times over the past twenty 
years with the constant supply of modern farm machines. The 
agricultural working people of the plain do nearly all 
categories of farm work ranging from ploughing to rice seedling 
plucking, rice transplanting, weeding, manuring and harvesting 
with machines. 
  Each cooperative farm in the plain has nearly one hundred 
technicians and experts. 
  Of late the dear leader Comrade Kim Chong-il sent 500 
tractors and some 250 lorries to the cooperative farms in the 
plain so as to further consolidate the material and technical 
foundations of agriculture. 
  The rural villages of plain have turned into modern 
socialist 
rural communities good to work and live in; they hold a big 
share in the nation's grain production. 
  Last year tens of thousands of more tons of grain was 
produced than in the previous year in the plain. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

