<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opening ROK-Japan-DPRK Sea Line Promoted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opening ROK-Japan-DPRK Sea Line Promoted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0604060094 Seoul MAEIL KYONGJE SINMUN in Korean 5 Apr 94 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> SK0604060094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul MAEIL KYONGJE SINMUN </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] An ROK shipping company is promoting the opening of 
a triangular sea route connecting Pusan port and North Korea's 
Chongjin port through Mogi port located on the southwest coast 
of Japan. 
  According to the Korea Maritime and Port Administration, 
Changyong Maritime Company, an inshore shipping company engaged 
in shipping between the ROK and Japan, represented by Kim 
Chong-su, recently applied to the National Unification Board 
[NUB] for permission to contact North Korean residents to open a 
regular sea route between Japan and North Korea for transporting 
agricultural and sea products. 
  Accordingly, the NUB consulted with the Korea Maritime and 
Port Administration, the office mainly concerned, to determine 
if it is acceptable for an ROK shipping company to open a sea 
route between Japan and North Korea. The Korea Maritime and 
Port Administration has informed the NUB that it is necessary 
for a domestic company to open a sea route between Japan and 
North Korea because this would help domestic shipping companies 
secure shipment territory in the East Sea economic area in the 
future. 

</TEXT>

