<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow: 2 Years Needed for Sakhalin Repatriation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow: 2 Years Needed for Sakhalin Repatriation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0504051594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0502 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0504051594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 5 (YONHAP) -- It will take at least two 
years for the South Korean Government to settle the repatriation 
of some 4,000 Koreans in Sakhalin, Radio Moscow reported Sunday. 
  The repatriation concerns the interests of South and North 
Korea as well as Russia, making the issue a difficult one to 
resolve, said the radio, monitored here by NAEWOE press. 
  Some 60,000 Koreans were taken to Sakhalin during World War 
II when Korea was under Japanese colonial rule, and about 4,000 
first-generation members remain, according to Radio Moscow. 
  More than expected said they wanted to return to Korea in a 
recent poll, apparently attracted by their mother country's 
economic growth and living standards, it reported. 
  Seoul insists that Tokyo is responsible for bringing them 
back to Korea since the majority were taken forcibly by the 
Japanese military to work at labor camps. 
  But many descendants of Koreans in Sakhalin have settled 
down 
with stable careers and Seoul officials predict the Russian 
Government would be unwilling to let them go. 

</TEXT>

