<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   France Allows Imports of ROK Marine Products </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    France Allows Imports of ROK Marine Products </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0204040094 Seoul THE KOREA HERALD in English 2 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> SK0204040094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA HERALD </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The French government has recently included South 
Korea in a list of countries that can export marine products to 
France, the Foreign Ministry said yesterday. Cheap imported 
maritime products have been gobbling up the French market, 
prompting Paris to draw up a list of a handful of countries 
outside the European Union that can continue selling such goods. 
Only five countries, including Argentina and Canada, had been 
put on the list publicized in February. 
  Seoul had an existing agreement with France on fisheries 
exports effective until January next year but was excluded from 
the list, the ministry said. The French government belatedly 
added eight more countries, including South Korea, Thailand and 
Singapore, to the list carried in its gazette March 26, it said. 
  South Korean exports of maritime products to France, which 
reached $21.9 million in 1991, decreased to $14.4 million in 
1992 and $10.8 million last year, according to the Seoul 
government's statistics. 

</TEXT>

