<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unification, Security Policy Coordination Council </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Unification, Security Policy Coordination Council </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0704020994 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0100 GMT 7 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0704020994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government has decided to form a Unification 
and Security Policy Coordination Council that will be in charge 
of summing up and adjusting policies on national unification and 
security to prevent confusion in policies on the North Korean 
nuclear issue. 
  The Unification and Security Policy Coordination Council was 
organized in a meeting on 7 April of security-related ministers 
presided over by President Kim Yong-sam. The council will hold 
meetings once or more a week with the vice unification minister 
as the chairman and the foreign and defense ministers, and the 
senior presidential aide on foreign affairs and security will 
analyze and examine the prevailing security situation and 
coordinate various offices' opinion. Anyone of the council 
members can immediately call a meeting of the council. 
  Proposing the organization of the Unification and Security 
Policy Coordination Council, President Kim Yong-sam asked 
security-related ministers to consult with one another more 
efficiently and to cope with situations promptly. 
  Regarding the rumor on North Korea's possession of nuclear 
weapons that was recently reported by some media, today's 
meeting came to the conclusion that there is no clear evidence 
to prove that North Korea possesses nuclear weapons at this 
point of time. 
  In addition, Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae reported that 
there has been no particular moves by the military around the 
truce line or in other areas in North Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5117 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas067_d_94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meetings `More Productive' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meetings `More Productive' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0704032994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0317 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0704032994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 7 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam 
instructed Thursday [7 April] a Unification and Security Policy 
Coordination Council be formed comprising National Unification 
Board [NUB], foreign, and defense ministers, National Security 
Planning agency director, chief presidential secretary, and 
senior secretary for foreign and national security affairs to 
effectively and consistently cope with the North Korean nuclear 
issue. 
  The deputy prime minister, concurrently the NUB minister, 
should head the coordination council for a meeting more than 
once a week and the meeting should be immediately held at a 
request from any member of the council, Kim ordered in a 
security-related cabinet meeting on Thursday morning. 
  The coordination meeting will ensure more cooperative and 
ready response to security issues, presidential spokesman Chu 
Ton-sik said afterward. 
  At Kim's instruction, Deputy Prime Minister Yi Yong-tok is 
expected to detail out operations of the council. 
  Because the soon-to-be-formed coordination meetings will be 
held regularly at least more than once a week unlike the 
existing high-level strategic meetings headed by the president 
or prime minister that opens when necessary, they will prove 
more productive and practical, Chu said. 
  Depending on the significance of the agenda, President Kim 
will personally chair the meetings, he said. 
  Developments in North Korea and other major countries were 
discussed in Thursday's breakfast discussion, Chu said. 
  It was concluded at the meeting that there was no solid 
evidence that North Korea owns nuclear weapons at present, he 
said. 
  Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae reported that there was no 
conspicuous military movement in North Korea. 

</TEXT>

