<H3> <TI>   Ranariddh, Hun Sen Urge KR Soldiers To Defect </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ranariddh, Hun Sen Urge KR Soldiers To Defect </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0604153694 Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0604153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Cambodian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Appeal of the Royal Government of Cambodia to the </F>
officers, the rank and file, and the compatriots living under 
the temporary control of the Khmer Rouge" [KR] dated 6 April -- 
recorded] 
  [Text] The Pailin region has a major economic, social, and 
cultural position in the Kingdom of Cambodia. The recalcitrant 
Khmer Rouge leaders still continue to occupy illegally this 
region and continue to cause considerable damage to national 
assets even after our country had entered the stage of national 
reconciliation, unity, and peace; after our most venerated 
monarch, His Majesty Norodom Sihanouk Varman, had ascended the 
throne to provide the coolest shade for all of us, his Cambodian 
subjects; and after the Royal Government of Cambodia [RGC] had 
come to power to lead and govern the nation in full legitimacy. 
Thus, with the noble intention of preserving peace and 
maintaining security for the people and preserving national 
unity and national reconciliation, the Khmer Royal Armed Forces 
[KRAF] made monumental efforts and braved all kinds of 
difficulties in entering and completely capturing the Pailin 
region on 19 March 1994. 
  With a high sense of responsibility toward the destiny of 
all 
Cambodians, the RGC would like to make another appeal to the 
officers, the rank and file, and the compatriots living under 
the temporary control of the Khmer Rouge. The brothers are 
asked to waste no time in finding all means to return to the 
national community and join the great family of Cambodians. 
  The RGC always has the fate and destiny of all of you at 
heart as already emphasized in previous appeals, especially in 
the statement made by the RGC on 25 March 1994. 
  1. As a matter of fact, the officers, noncommissioned 
officers, and men still serving in the ranks of the Khmer Rouge 
are urged to hurry up and present themselves before the KRAF and 
the competent authorities in the region. You will be accorded 
all due attention and your rights, privileges, grades, and 
duties will be assured in the same way as has been done by the 
RGC toward the thousands of former Khmer Rouge officers, 
noncommissioned officers, and men who have already awakened to 
the call and joined the national community and the RGC. 
  2. As for the civilians who have been forcibly taken along 
by Khmer Rouge leaders, they should hurry up and liberate 
themselves from the claws of the Khmer Rouge by immediately 
contacting the KRAF and the competent authorities protecting the 
region. You will be welcomed and given all necessary assistance 
by the RGC and you will receive land and houses in accordance 
with the law. 
  3. As far as the compatriots who take temporary refuge in 
Thailand are concerned, the RGC will continue to contact and 
negotiate with the representatives of the Thai Government in 
order to bring them back to our sacred Angkorian land with the 
assistance of various international organizations. Concerning 
the repatriation of these refugees, the RGC's good-will and 
sincere stance is that the repatriation should proceed through a 
negotiation between our RGC and the government of the country 
concerned on the basis of humanitarian principles, 
voluntariness, noncoercion, and respect for the right of the 
concerned brothers to make a choice. Any brothers who wish to 
remain in Pailin or to go to any other fully safe regions will 
be allowed to do so with the assistance of the RGC. 
  The RGC is confident that the country concerned will do its 
best to help and support this righteous cause by respecting 
Cambodia's independence, sovereignty, and territorial integrity 
and refrain from interfering in each other's internal affairs as 
stipulated in the 23 October 1991 Paris agreement. 
  [Signed] Prince Krompreah Norodom Ranaridddh, first prime 
minister 
  Samdech Hun Sen, second prime minister 
  [Dated] 6 April 1994, Phnom Penh 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

