</HEADER>

<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vote of G-15 Sought Against Wage-Trade Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vote of G-15 Sought Against Wage-Trade Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0704154794 Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network in English 
1300 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0704154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Malaysia hopes to get the support of other G-15 
[Group of 15] and South countries to oppose a wage-trade link 
proposal with a view to setting the minimum global wage 
standards at the upcoming General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade, GATT, meeting in Marrakesh, Morocco. Foreign Minister 
Datuk Abdullah Haji Ahmad Badawi said he was hopeful that the 
G-15 and South countries could meet prior to the 15 April GATT 
meeting to establish a common stand against the proposal by the 
U.S. and France. The Uruguay round trade accord is to be signed 
by 120 countries at the meeting next week. The U.S. and France 
were proposing that a wage-trade link be discussed at the 
meeting, setting in motion a debate on the proposed minimum 
global wage standards. Datuk Abdullah was speaking to reporters 
after meeting China's vice minister for foreign affairs, Tang 
Jianxuan, at Wisma Putera [Ministry of Foreign Affairs] in Kuala 
Lumpur. The four-man delegation arrived on Tuesday for a 
three-day visit to Kuala Lumpur and Melaka. 
  Reiterating that linking workers' rights with trade was 
unjustified, he hoped the G-15 along with other South countries 
would be united in opposing the link. The G-15 needed to 
discuss and coordinate support from all countries of the South, 
adding that the proposal would have a serious impact on the 
economies of the developing countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5136 </DOCNO>
