<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Sea Exercise With Thai Navy Begins 4 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Joint Sea Exercise With Thai Navy Begins 4 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0604104094 Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES in English 5 Apr 
94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> BK0604104094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Langkawi, Mon -- The navies and marine police units 
of Malaysia and Thailand today began a five-day joint training 
exercise with the main objective of ironing out communication 
difficulties. 
  The manoeuvres, the 21st in the Seaex Thamal series, will 
take place off Langkawi in Malaysia and Satun and Phuket Island 
in Thailand. 
  About 300 personnel and eight vessels -- four from each 
country -- are taking part in the exercise launched by Malaysian 
Internal Security and Public Order director Ghazali Yaacob at 
the Bukit Malut Marine police base. 
  The joint forces will also test their co-operation in 
patrolling formation, enforcement and search-and-rescue 
operations, as well as technical matters. 

