<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo `Expects' Resumption of U.S. Trade Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo `Expects' Resumption of U.S. Trade Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704111394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1048 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704111394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 7 KYODO -- A top Japanese trade 
official said Thursday [7 April] he expects Foreign Minister 
Tsutomu Hata to agree with U.S. Trade Representative Mickey 
Kantor on resumption of stalled bilateral talks on a new trade 
framework. 
  Hata is expected to meet Kantor in Marrakech, Morocco, on 
April 15 as the two visit there for the signing of a new global 
trade pact known as the Uruguay Round Trade Agreement. The 
Hata-Kantor meeting is expected to produce "good results" as 
there are signs that Washington is softening its stance on 
bilateral economic issues, said the top official at the Ministry 
of International Trade and Industry. 
  The official stressed the need to reach agreement by around 
June 10 when Emperor Akihito visits the United States and 
suggested that Japan should decide on "drastic" measures to do 
so. 
  As for U.S. policy on Japan, the official said the issue of 
how to deal with the nuclear problem in North Korea seems to be 
given top priority in U.S. policy on Japan. "It seems that the 
Clinton administration to date has separated security issues 
from trade issues in trade negotiations with Japan but recently 
they appear to have linked security issues with trade issues," 
the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

