<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   UK Minister Ends Three-Day Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UK Minister Ends Three-Day Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0704161394 Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network in English 
1300 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0704161394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] British Secretary of State for Education John Patten 
says he sensed a great desire on the part of Malaysia and 
Britain to bring business back on normal footing as soon as 
possible. He said this was his impression from meetings with 
various ministers and British businessmen during his three-day 
visit to Malaysia which ended today. He was anxious that the 
flow of investment from the United Kingdom into Malaysia 
continues because he thinks that it would be a benefit to both 
countries. Patten, the highest-ranking official to visit 
Malaysia since the Malaysian Government slapped a ban on 
awarding government projects to British companies in February. 
Patten said that once he returned home, he would try his best 
to give a picture that relations between the two countries were 
getting better again and that investment opportunities in 
Malaysia were too good for British investors to miss. 

</TEXT>

