<H3> <TI>   Foreigners Urge End to ROK Security Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreigners Urge End to ROK Security Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0704153094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1511 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0704153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["S. Korean `National Security Law' Must Be Scrapped </F>
Immediately" -- KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, April 7 (KCNA) -- Voices strongly urging 
the abrogation of the "National Security Law [NSL]" in South 
Korea are ringing out from different countries. 
  J.O. Adeloju, chairman of the Nigerian Committee for 
Supporting the Peaceful Reunification of Korea, said in a press 
statement that the "National Security Law" of South Korea is the 
fascist law which defines North Korea as "an anti-state 
organization", barring free travels and exchange between the 
North and the South. 
  If the North-South dialogue is to progress successfully and 
peace and reunification of the Korean peninsula to be achieved 
at an early date, it is necessary to immediately and 
unconditionally scrap the NSL, he contended. 
  The Mozambican Committee for Friendship with the People of 
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea said in a statement 
that the South Korean authorities must know clearly that they 
can never evade the blame for their treason in blocking the 
national reunification, if they refuse to repeal the "National 
Security Law" despite warnings from the world people. 
  The Indonesian paper IN O SIAN OTSERVER carried an article 
branding the "NSL" as an obstacle to the materialization of 
democracy in South Korea. 

</TEXT>

