<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sihanouk To Meet Khieu Samphan in Beijing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sihanouk To Meet Khieu Samphan in Beijing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0804065094 (Clandestine) Voice of the Great National Union 
Front of Cambodia in Cambodian 2330 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0804065094 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Voice of the Great National Union 
Front of Cambodia </F>

<F P=105>  Cambodian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] 1. On 29 March 1994, after receiving news that King 
Norodom Sihanouk and the queen would return to the motherland on 
8 April, His Excellency [H.E.] Khieu Samphan, chairman of the 
Party of Democratic Kampuchea, sent a message to his majesty the 
king. Here is the essence: 
  I am very happy to learn that his majesty the king has been 
discharged from the hospital in good health and that the king 
and queen will return to meet with the children of our 
motherland on 8 April. 
  The entire Cambodian nation and people very much rejoice 
over 
this great event. I will be in Phnom Penh on 8 April to join 
our nation and people in welcoming the king on this joyous 
occasion. As the king has a tight schedule and his health is 
not yet fully back to normal, I do not dare ask to see the king 
and the queen at this time. Please allow me to meet with you 
and the queen on a day you deem appropriate. 
  2. On 1 April, the king and queen answered H.E. Khieu 
Samphan's message through the king's Secretariat in Phnom Penh. 
The king said he would be pleased to receive H.E. Khieu Samphan 
and a delegation at the Royal Palace at 1000 on 13 April. 
  3. On 2 April, after learning that the king and the queen 
had agreed to receive H.E. Khieu Samphan and a delegation on 13 
April, H.E. Khieu Samphan addressed another message to his 
majesty the king. Here is the essence: 
  Please allow me to express my most profound gratitude to the 
king and queen for agreeing to receive me and a delegation at 
the Royal Palace at 1000 on 13 April. As I informed the king in 
my message dated 29 March, my colleagues and I want to express 
our respect, fond sentiments, and warmest welcome directly upon 
the arrival of his majesty the king and the queen at Pochentong 
Airport. My presence could cause some protocol difficulties, 
however, as well as security problems. 
  For this reason, please allow me to send a delegation to 
Phnom Penh, with H.E. Chan Youran as my representative, to 
express directly my warmest welcome to the king and queen at 
Pochentong Airport and to contact the king's Secretariat to 
prepare for my 12 April trip to meet the king and queen at the 
Royal Palace on 13 April at 1000, as scheduled. 
  4. On 5 April, his majesty the king sent another message to 
H.E. Khieu Samphan through the king's Secretariat, informing 
H.E. Khieu Samphan that there are many problems concerning his 
planned trip to Phnom Penh. These problems result from the fact 
that the Cambodian state authorities -- whether the police or 
the force accompanying the visit -- do not have the goodwill to 
give any consideration to the arrival, escort, or return of H.E. 
Khieu Samphan. They also will not give any consideration 
whatsoever to H.E. Khieu Samphan's security in Phnom Penh. 
  On top of this, there is no guarantee -- even 60 percent -- 
of H.E. Khieu Samphan's security, or for that of the Democratic 
Kampuchean delegation as it is traveling from Pochentong to 
Phnom Penh, during its stay in Phnom Penh, or in the Royal 
Palace. 
  The king said: I cannot find any trusted person to accompany 
the Democratic Kampuchean delegation from Pochentong to Phnom 
Penh and back. With such a bad situation, it is better for you 
to meet me in Beijing in June. 

</TEXT>

