<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Envoy Warns of Japanese Nuclear `Threat' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Envoy Warns of Japanese Nuclear `Threat' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0804060194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0553 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0804060194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New Delhi, April 8 (YONHAP) -- A North Korean 
ambassador warned Friday that his country will go nuclear, 
accusing Japan of posing an atomic threat to the Korean 
peninsula. 
  The threat of Japanese nuclear weapons development is being 
actualized, North Korean envoy to India Cha Pong-chu said in a 
keynote speech to the UN Economic and Social Commission for Asia 
and the Pacific (ESCAP). 
  Tokyo currently possesses enough plutonium to make 6,500 
nuclear weapons, Cha claimed, demanding that the Japanese 
Government announce to the world it will not go nuclear. 
  If Japan did choose the nuclear option, the inter-Korean 
agreement on denuclearization would become meaningless, he said, 
reasoning that North Korea would then have to pursue its own 
nuclear program. 
  Cha, a former vice foreign minister, said in an earlier 
interview with YONHAP News Agency that Pyongyang would decide 
whether to produce nuclear weapons after considering all 
external threats. 

</TEXT>

