<H3> <TI>   `Overall Situation' Considered </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Overall Situation' Considered </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0804030894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0258 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0804030894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 8 (YONHAP) -- The government held the 
first meeting on unification and security policy coordination at 
the South-North dialogue office on Friday to review its overall 
policy toward North Korea. 
  The meeting, presided over by Minister of the National 
Unification Board (NUB) Yi Yong-tok, decided to discuss all 
unification matters, diplomacy related to the North and security 
to coordinate the opinions of different ministries. 
  The various ministries and secretaries will also push ahead 
with unification- and security-related policies under the 
principle that the government must seek progress in inter-Korean 
relations. 
  President Kim Yong-sam Thursday instructed that a 
Unification 
and Security Policy Coordination Council be formed. The council 
comprises the minister of the National Unification Board, the 
foreign and defense ministers, the director of the Agency for 
National Security Planning, the chief presidential secretary and 
the senior secretary for foreign and national security affairs. 
  NUB Minister Yi said after the meeting, "We looked into the 
overall situation on unification and security after adoption of 
the U.N. Security Council's presidential statement and rupture 
of inter-Korean working-level contact." 
  "We will discuss every policy to adjust differences between 
ministries." 
  The coordination meetings will be held regularly more than 
once a week, and President Kim himself will chair the sessions 
when necessary. 

</TEXT>

