<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Asks DPRK To Improve Loggers' Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Asks DPRK To Improve Loggers' Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0804011094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0044 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0804011094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 8 (YONHAP) -- Russia has asked North 
Korea to allow its loggers in Siberia to carry passports and 
move freely through the logging yards, a lawmaker said Wednesday. 
  Rep. Kang Sin-cho, chairman of a fact-finding subcommittee 
of 
the National Assembly's Committee on Foreign Affairs and 
Reunification, made the remark after attending a closed-door 
meeting with government officials. 
  He said Moscow is demanding that Pyongyang improve the human 
rights of North Koreans working at logging yards in Siberia. 
  "On-the-spot examination by the fact-finding subcommittee of 
the Siberian logging yards is a delicate matter related to 
diplomatic relations between South Korea and Russia as well as 
inter-Korean relations. Therefore, we plan to decide on when to 
go to Siberia after fully consulting with the government," he 
said. 
  Pyongyang is negotiating with Moscow to renew their forestry 
agreement which expired at the end of last year, but Russia is 
demanding that a new provision securing the human rights of 
North Korean loggers be added to the new pact. 
  Some 16,000 to 20,000 North Koreans are working in 
Pyongyang-run logging yards in Siberia, with hundreds having 
escaped to roam throughout Russia or seeking asylum in South 
Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5215 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas068_d_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-068 </AU>
