<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Official on Asylum for DPRK Loggers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Official on Asylum for DPRK Loggers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0804132094 Seoul YONHAP in English 1306 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0804132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New Delhi, April 8 (YONHAP) -- Russian Vice Foreign 
Minister Aleksandr Panov said here on Friday that if South Korea 
wishes it, Russia would send all those North Korean loggers who 
had escaped from their logging yards in Siberia to South Korea. 
  Panov, now here to attend the 50th U.N. Economic and Social 
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) meeting, told the 
YONHAP news agency that there would be no problem in permitting 
their asylum in South Korea. 
  Saying that talks were going on with North Korea over 
whether 
to continue to keep North Korean logging yards in Siberia, the 
Russian vice foreign minister said a new agreement could be 
concluded before long taking into account the views of human 
rights organizations concerned about the rights of North Korean 
loggers. 
  With regard to his recent remarks that Russia would support 
North Korea if it is invaded, Panov said that Russia is the 
successor to the former Soviet Union and that the agreements 
signed between the USSR and North Korea still remain valid. 
  "If we repeal USSR-North Korea agreements overnight, it 
would 
lead to a great confusion," he said. "But, we are 
re-interpreting some of the clauses of such agreements now that 
things have changed." 
  Russia is seeking ways to cope with the changed reality 
while 
keeping the existing agreements without offending North Korea if 
possible, Panov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

