<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Students Demonstrate Against Uruguay Round </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Students Demonstrate Against Uruguay Round </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0804133894 Seoul KBS-1 Television Network in Korean 1219 
GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0804133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Hwang Sang-mo] </F>
  [Text] Students who had restrained themselves from staging 
demonstrations for some time took to the streets again to demand 
renegotiations on the revised Uruguay Round implementation plan. 
  Approximately 5,000 students of 22 Seoul universities, 
including Hanyang and Kyonghui Universities, gathered at 
Chongnyangni Station, Chongmyo Park, and other places in Seoul 
and held meetings to oppose the ratification of the Uruguay 
Round implementation plan. The students called the revision of 
the Uruguay Round implementation plan an antistate act that 
would crush agriculture. They demanded renegotiations with the 
United States on basic agricultural products. They also 
demanded that the National Assembly not ratify the 
implementation plan and opposed the adoption of the Morocco 
protocol composed of implementation plans of each state 
scheduled for 12 April. 
  Approximately 5,000 students of some 110 regional 
universities, including Pusan, Chonnam, and Kyongbuk 
Universities, held meetings this afternoon to oppose the 
adoption of the Uruguay Round protocol and the National 
Assembly's ratification and staged street demonstrations. 
  In particular, students of eight universities in Pusan and 
South Kyongsang Province, including Pusan and Tonga Universities 
declared a class boycott for today and tomorrow. 
  Most of today's gatherings were peaceful, and there was no 
confrontation between police and students. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

