<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges New Parliamentary Group </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Urges New Parliamentary Group </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0804122494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1154 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804122494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 8 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa renewed his call on Friday to create a new large 
parliamentary group of various political parties within the 
House of Representatives with his Japan New Party serving as its 
core. 
  Hosokawa made the appeal at a plenary session of his party's 
38 legislators a few hours after announcing his decision to give 
up the premiership, JNP legislators said. 
  "We have to assemble people with the ideal of reform while 
making our party the core of the new group," Hosokawa said. 
  The premier proposed naming the new group "Reform." 
  The JNP legislators agreed to give Hosokawa a mandate to 
decide how to proceed with the project to form the new 
parliamentary group. 
  The idea had earlier come under a barrage of criticism from 
the new party Sakigake (Harbinger) and the Social Democratic 
Party, which charged that such a proposal, if realized, would 
lead to the formation of a new large party amalgamating the JNP, 
Shinseito and Komeito. 
  The premier's renewal of the call may add fuel to a 
simmering 
intracoalition rivalry between the Sakigake-SDP camp and the 
JNP- Shinseito-Komeito camp at a time when the coalition is 
moving to pick a successor to Hosokawa, political analysts said. 
  Hosokawa also told the plenary session he had decided to 
dissolve the current JNP-Sakigake parliamentary group, the 
legislators said. 
  Meanwhile, JNP executives said the party had decided to 
report the formation of the new parliamentary group "Reform" to 
the Secretariat of the lower chamber. 
  In addition to the 38 JNP legislators, two United Social 
Democratic Party legislators had decided to join the new group, 
they added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

