<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Hosokawa Resignation Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to Hosokawa Resignation Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Major' U.S. Ties Change Unlikely </H4>

<F P=102> OW0804105994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1046 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 8 KYODO -- The resignation of Japanese 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa is unlikely to lead to a major 
change in Tokyo's economic ties with the United States, a senior 
trade ministry official said Friday. 
  However, Hosokawa's surprise announcement may set back the 
resumption of the stalled trade "framework" talks between Tokyo 
and Washington, said the official at the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry, who declined to be named. 
  But he quickly added the fundamentals of the accord reached 
between the previous Japanese administration of Kiichi Miyazawa 
and U.S. President Bill Clinton last July to establish a new 
framework are still valid. 
  Hosokawa took over Miyazawa's trade policy toward the U.S. 
that rules out the use of numerical targets to measure the 
results of Japan's efforts to boost imports and the next prime 
minister is likely also to respect the policy, the MITI official 
said. 
  Although optimistic about the fundamental framework of 
Japan's economic ties with the U.S., the official confirmed that 
prospects for an early breakthrough in the bilateral trade talks 
have become clouded following the latest political developments 
surrounding Hosokawa. 
  Japan regarded the planned meeting between Foreign Minister 
Tsutomu Hata and U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor in 
Marrakesh, Morocco, on April 15 as "the best opportunity" to 
open the way for resumption of the framework talks, the official 
said. 
  "But the situation is now completely fluid," the official 
said, noting it is "impossible to foresee developments still to 
unfold," including even whether or not Hata will go to Morocco. 
  Hata, the leader of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], a major 
coalition member, has been tipped as a candidate to succeed 
Hosokawa. 
  The premier's resignation also casts a shadow over Japan's 
pledge to announce concrete market-opening measures by the end 
of June or before the July summit of the seven major 
industrialized countries in Naples, the MITI official said. 
  It is too early to say whether a schedule change regarding 
the June market-opening package is necessary, but any prime 
minister replacing Hosokawa should have "a stronger power base" 
in order to get the framework talks rolling again, the official 
said. 
  The official said Hosokawa's successor would not likely 
"reverse the trend of deregulations" established by the Hosokawa 
administration. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5223 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas068_a_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-068 </AU>
