<DATE1>  8 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Hosokawa Resignation Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to Hosokawa Resignation Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata-Kantor Meeting `Uncertain' </H4>

<F P=102> OW0804084394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0831 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804084394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 8 KYODO -- Japan's trade minister on 
Friday [8 April] stressed the urgent need to create a new 
political framework to prevent a further stall in Japan-U.S. 
trade talks. 
  International Trade and Industry Minister Hiroshi Kumagai 
called an emergency press conference after Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa offered his resignation earlier in the day. 
  "The situation surrounding Japan-U.S. ties requires urgent 
action," Kumagai said. "There is not much time left before 
June." 
  Japan pledged to show concrete market-opening plans in June 
or before the leaders of the world's seven major economies 
gather in Naples in July for their annual summit meeting. 
  Kumagai said he understands Hosokawa's resignation offer, 
saying the prime minister must have reached the decision as a 
way to take responsibility for his financial dealings which have 
paralyzed Diet discussion of the fiscal 1994 budget. 
  Hosokawa's coalition government was formed with top priority 
on establishing high ethical standards for politicians, Kumagai 
said. 
  The trade minister said the Hosokawa administration has 
broken through many difficult problems its predecessor, the 
Liberal Democratic Party, was unable to handle, Kumagai said, 
citing political and administrative reforms, rice market 
opening, deregulations and tax reforms. 
  What Hosokawa achieved is worthy of being remembered in an 
historical context, Kumagai said. 
  Kumagai severely criticized the LDP for boycotting debate 
over this year's budget. "The LDP is committing a suicidal act 
that denies the fundamental function of the parliament," he said. 
  Kumagai said he is uncertain whether the planned meeting 
between Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata and U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor in Morocco on April 15 will take 
place as scheduled. 
  The meeting was intended to seek a breakthrough in the 
stalled trade "framework" talks between Tokyo and Washington. 
  "Paving the way for resumption of the framework talks is 
something that should be taken care of by our cabinet but I 
don't know what will happen," Kumagai said. 
  Hata, the leader of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], a major 
coalition party, is tipped as a candidate to succeed Hosokawa. 
  Concerning a government to succeed the Hosokawa 
administration, Kumagai said it should be formed after parties 
concerned agree at least on the controversial tax issue. 
  The current ruling coalition parties were sharply divided 
over how to finance tax cuts. This created political confusion 
earlier in the day that delayed formulation of the fiscal 1994 
budget. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

