<H4>    MITI Official on U.S. Trade Talks </H4>

<F P=102> OW0804062394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0617 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804062394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 8 KYODO -- Japan-U.S. trade talks will 
remain deadlocked due to Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's 
announcement that he intends to resign, a high-ranking official 
of the Ministry of International Trade and Industry said Friday 
[8 April]. 
  "Though the bilateral trade framework talks are likely to 
resume between Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata and U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor next week, the development will be 
unclear," said the official. 
  Hata is expected to meet Kantor in Marrakech, Morroco, next 
week at the signing ceremony for the global trade pact concluded 
in the Uruguay Round last December under the General Agreement 
on Tariffs and Trade. 
  "I had believed Hosokawa may announce his intention to step 
down around weekend but today's sudden announcement is a 
betrayal against expectation of most Japanese," the official who 
asked not to be identified. 

</TEXT>

