<DOCNO> FBIS4-5225 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas068_a_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-068 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Hosokawa Resignation Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to Hosokawa Resignation Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Coalition Parties Discuss Response </H4>

<F P=102> OW0804153294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1435 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Tokyo, April 8 KYODO -- Embattled Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa made a surprise announcement Friday [8 April] 
of his intention to resign because of controversy over personal 
financial deals and the resultant parliamentary paralysis 
crippling his eight-month-old administration. 
  Hosokawa's bombshell announcement prompted the seven 
coalition parties to scramble to the task of picking his 
successor. 
  Although Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] and Komeito [Clean 
Government Party], key parties in the coalition, voiced support 
for Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata who 
leads Shinseito, the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and 
Democratic Socialist Party (DSP) expressed disaffection with the 
proposal. 
  The 56-year-old Hosokawa told a hurriedly-arranged news 
conference he had decided to give up the office of prime 
minister to take "moral and political responsibility" for a 
fresh financial scandal and the current stalemate of the Diet. 
  "A new problem has come to light. New suspicions emerged 
that my political office entrusted a certain person with 
managing my personal financial means, raking in profits for a 
few years since 1981," the premier said. 
  "The suspicion is that his management may have involved some 
illegalities, although the person, who is my old friend, asked 
for permission to manage my personal money, saying it would 
definitely be invested in a profitable manner," he said. 
  He said the new revelation came on top of controversy about 
100 million yen that Hosokawa described as a loan from a 
trucking company already at the center of a money-and-mob 
scandal. 
  The opposition camp held up Diet debate on the fiscal 1994 
fiscal budget, saying Hosokawa should first agree to the 
opposition demand to have his financial aide Masatoshi Miyama 
testify as a witness to clear up suspicions on the allegedly 
questionable finances. 
  Hosokawa officially offered his resignation at an emergency 
cabinet meeting after making a surprise announcement to a 
hastily summoned meeting of leaders of the coalition partners. 
  In a second get-together of the coalition leaders later in 
the day, Komeito Secretary General Yuichi Ichikawa insisted that 
the coalition parties first narrow the differences in their 
defense and diplomatic policies before making a decision on 
whether to maintain the current combination of parties. 
  Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa, a behind-the-scene 
strategist, Japan New Party leader Masuo Matsuoka and DSP 
Secretary General Takashi Yonezawa threw their weight behind the 
Komeito proposal, while the Socialists vehemently opposed it. 
  The coalition leaders only agreed to resume discussion 
Saturday afternoon, coalition officials said. 
  Political analysts pointed to the possibility that the 
coalition might try to form a new coalition by integrating some 
legislators from the opposition Liberal Democratic Party [LDP] 
even at the risk of alienating the SDP. 
  However, the LDP quickly vowed to block any attempts by the 
coalition to win over its legislators and instead to establish a 
new coalition government led by itself. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

