<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Hosokawa Resignation Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to Hosokawa Resignation Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata on Trip to Morocco Prospect </H4>

<F P=102> OW0804094294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0912 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804094294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 8 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata brushed aside suggestions Friday [8 April] that he become 
the next prime minister in the wake of Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa's announcement that he will resign. 
  Hata, who concurrently serves as the deputy prime minister, 
told a hastily arranged press conference at the Foreign Ministry 
that he considers it important to play the role of making 
adjustments within the coalition government rather than becoming 
the next prime minister. 
  Hata also indicated he may go ahead with his planned trip to 
Marrakech, Morocco, next week to attend the signing ceremony of 
a global trade accord under the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade (GATT). 
  Since Hosokawa instructed cabinet ministers to fulfill their 
duties until the end, his scheduled trip to Marrakesh has not 
been totally scrapped, Hata said. 
  As for Hosokawa's successor, Hata said he wants the person 
to 
be someone who has the "same ambition to further promote 
reforms" and who wants to create a more stable government. 
  Turning to the possible effects the latest development would 
give to international affairs, Hata said it would give negative 
influence not only on Japan-U.S. relations, which has been sour 
over trade disputes, but on the rest of the world. 
  He said it would give the world anxiety concerning Japanese 
politics so that it is important to stabilize the government as 
early as possible. 
  He also said Japan should explain about the course of 
Japanese politics at the Marrakech meeting. 
  "Japan has become a country which could influence various 
countries," Hata said. "So there should not be a delay in 
politics not even for a day." 
  Hata, who was expected to meet U.S. Trade Representative 
Mickey Kantor in Marrakech, Morocco, said he thinks it possible 
to hold "frank" discussions with Kantor since Japan's 
determination to promote free trade and to make efforts to make 
a more open market remains unchanged no matter how the domestic 
political situation is. 
  "There aren't many options concerning what Japan can do," he 
said. 
  The foreign minister also indicated there will be no problem 
in dealing with the problems involving North Korea's alleged 
development of nuclear weapons because the Japanese 
administration has the consistency and continuity of policies. 
  Hata, also the leader of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] 
which broke away from the Liberal Democratic Party, said he told 
an extraordinary cabinet meeting that he wants Hosokawa to stick 
to the post. 
  But Hata said he cannot dissuade Hosokawa because he has 
already officially announced his intention to step down. 
  He described Friday's development as one of the 
"aftershocks" 
from a major "diastrophism" last June, when Shinseito split from 
the LDP, which led to the birth of the coalition government, 
indicating that it may be a chance toward a major reorganization 
of the political world. 
  He reiterated the need to create two stable political 
forces, 
saying the coalition government of seven parties had difficulty 
in making a single decision. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

