<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Basic Policies' on Rate Increases Adopted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Basic Policies' on Rate Increases Adopted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0804035494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0336 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804035494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 8 KYODO -- The government moved Friday 
[8 April] to minimize the possible damage to the economy of 
planned hikes in utility and other public service charges by 
adopting what it called a set of "basic policies" on the 
proposed increases. 
  Key cabinet members agreed that the suggested hikes in 
telephone, taxi, medicine and many other public service charges 
should be permitted if they are "really inevitable" and only 
after due consideration is paid to their possible impact on the 
economy. The timing and scale of such hikes should be 
determined so they will not hurt the economy, the ministers said. 
  They also agreed that the charges should be raised on 
condition that services operators implement thorough 
restructuring in the future, officials said. 
  The meeting brought together Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii, and other related 
government officials. 
  It came as public concern mounted over a string of proposed 
hikes of charges for public services that some critics say will 
erode the benefits of the government's planned tax cuts and 
hamper the recovery of the economy. 
  Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. (NTT), for instance, 
has 
applied for government permission to raise the basic rate it 
charges telephone owners by an average 18 percent, as well as 
hiking its directory inquiries rates. 
  The planned rate hikes run against the Hosokawa government's 
much-touted policy of paying greater attention to consumers' 
interests. 
  The cabinet ministers stressed the need to bring Japan's 
public services rates into line with those of other countries, 
which are generally lower, officials said. 
  They said the ministers also agreed that the "basic 
policies" 
should be complied with when local governments give permission 
to raise bus fares and other public services charges in their 
areas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

