<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, Hanoi Said To Differ on Economic Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo, Hanoi Said To Differ on Economic Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604084794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0829 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0604084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ho Chi Minh City, April 6 KYODO -- Business leaders 
from Japan and Vietnam differed on ways to promote Japan's 
direct investment in Vietnam as they opened a joint economic 
session Wednesday [6 April], conference sources said. 
  The sources said the Vietnamese side urged Japan to 
accelerate direct investment in the country to help promote its 
economic development. 
  The Japanese delegation took a cautious stance on the issue, 
seeking Hanoi to consolidate legal and infrastructural measures 
to promote the inflow of Japanese capital, they said. 
  The Japanese panel expressed disappointment at slow progress 
in improvement particularly in electric power, transportation 
and communications industries, and the double pricing system for 
public utilities rates, the sources said. 
  The conference, the second session of a joint Japan-Vietnam 
economic conference, drew attention as it took place amid the 
changing international situation in favor of Vietnam, such as 
resumption of aid by international financial institutions and 
the lifting of economic sanctions by the United States, they 
said. 
  The 117-member Japanese delegation consists of 
representatives from about 60 major corporations. The 
Vietnamese panel was led by Vice Premier Tran Duc Luong. 

</TEXT>

